Despite some concerns about very elderly patients due to bleeding risk, current evidence supports effective delivery of acute stroke treatments—including tPA—in older adults via structured protocols involving rapid response teams and interdisciplinary collaboration; thus, adequacy hinges more on system-level implementation than patient age. \boxed{C} Based solely on retrieval results, there remains no explicit confirmation that all older patients achieve optimal outcomes despite existing structural efforts improving equity in access. 

Final summary:

The provided evidence indicates that while certain subgroups among older adults may face heightened risks, systematic interventions such as prompt emergency responses and comprehensive post-stroke management enable appropriate and accessible care even in aging populations. Therefore, it does not support a blanket claim of inadequacy but instead highlights context-dependent variability influenced by healthcare structure—not inherent limitations tied only to advanced age.\boxed{C}

